{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643265"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:51:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:51:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17994"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17994"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.29,0.08,0.16,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10708"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79174"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10708"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17994"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64526"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10053"},{"type":"tags","id":"10058"},{"type":"tags","id":"10069"},{"type":"tags","id":"10770"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24930"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24934"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79174"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a common observation in patients with type 2 diabetes following very low carbohydrate dietary interventions?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diminishing effects over time most likely due to weight loss","Varying effects on dyslipidaemia","Least pronounced effects seen with continued diabetes medications","Consistent improvement in all lipid parameters","Reported improvement in quality of life"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVery low carbohydrate diets are often used in the management of type 2 diabetes to improve glycaemic control and promote weight loss. However, the effects on lipid profiles can be variable. \u003Cstrong\u003EVarying effects on dyslipidemia\u003C/strong\u003E are commonly observed, with some patients experiencing improvements in triglycerides and HDL cholesterol, while others may see an increase in LDL cholesterol. This variability is due to individual differences in metabolism and response to dietary changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiminishing effects over time\u003C/strong\u003E can occur as the body adapts to the diet, and weight loss plateaus, reducing the initial benefits seen in glycemic control and insulin sensitivity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReported improvement in quality of life\u003C/strong\u003E is often noted by patients due to weight loss and improved energy levels, but this is not a universal experience and can vary based on individual preferences and adherence to the diet.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eleast pronounced effects seen with continued diabetes medications\u003C/strong\u003E occur because these medications can mask the full impact of dietary changes on blood sugar levels, making it harder to assess the diet\u0027s effectiveness independently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConsistent improvement in all lipid parameters\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically observed, as the effects on lipid profiles can be mixed, with some parameters improving and others worsening depending on the individual response to the diet.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Low carbohydrate diets can lead to initial improvements in type 2 diabetes management, but these effects may diminish over time.","Low carbohydrate diets can have varying effects on lipid profiles, sometimes improving or worsening dyslipidemia.","Patients on low carbohydrate diets often report an improved quality of life due to weight loss and improved glycemic control.","The effects of low carbohydrate diets are less pronounced when diabetes medications are continued, as these medications can mask dietary effects."],"references":["Silverii GA, Botarelli L, Dicembrini I, Girolamo V, Santagiuliana F, Monami M, Mannucci E. Low-carbohydrate diets and type 2 diabetes treatment: a meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials. Acta Diabetol. 2020 Nov;57(11):1375-1382. doi: 10.1007/s00592-020-01568-8. Epub 2020 Jul 8. PMID: 32638087.","Currenti W, Losavio F, Quiete S, Alanazi AM, Messina G, Polito R, Ciolli F, Zappal\u00e0 RS, Galvano F, Cincione RI. Comparative Evaluation of a Low-Carbohydrate Diet and a Mediterranean Diet in Overweight/Obese Patients with Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus: A 16-Week Intervention Study. Nutrients. 2023 Dec 27;16(1):95. doi: 10.3390/nu16010095. PMID: 38201924; PMCID: PMC10781045.","Gilbert-Barness, E., Barness, L. A., \u0026 Farrell, P. M. (Eds.). (2017). Metabolic diseases: foundations of clinical management, genetics, and pathology. IOS Press","Lanham-New, S. A., Macdonald, I. A., \u0026 Roche, H. M. (Eds.). (2011). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Roche, H. M., Macdonald, I. A., Schols, A. M., \u0026 Lanham-New, S. A. (Eds.). (2024). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64526"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17994"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64526"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T16:13:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T16:14:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"item